INSERT INTO [constellations] ([name], [description], [link]) VALUES
('Orion', 'Orion is a prominent constellation located on the celestial equator and visible throughout the world. It is one of the most easily recognizable constellations due to its distinctive shape and the presence of several bright stars. Orion is named after a hunter in Greek mythology and is often depicted as a man holding a club and wearing a lion''s skin. The constellation is made up of several bright stars, including Betelgeuse, Rigel, and Bellatrix. These stars form the distinctive shape of the constellation, with Betelgeuse marking the shoulder of the hunter, Rigel marking the foot, and Bellatrix marking the shoulder. In addition to these bright stars, Orion also contains several other interesting celestial objects. The Orion Nebula, for example, is a bright cloud of gas and dust located within the constellation that is visible to the naked eye. The constellation is also home to several star clusters and binary star systems, making it a rich area for astronomical study. Overall, Orion is a fascinating constellation to observe and learn about, and it has played a significant role in human history and culture for thousands of years.', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f5/OrionCC.jpg'),
('Ursa Major', 'Ursa Major, also known as the Great Bear, is a large constellation located in the northern sky. It is one of the most easily recognizable constellations due to the presence of the Big Dipper, a group of seven bright stars that form the shape of a ladle or dipper. The Big Dipper is located within Ursa Major and is often used as a starting point for finding other constellations in the night sky. Ursa Major is named after a bear in Greek mythology and is associated with several different myths and legends. In some cultures, the constellation is seen as a guardian or protector, while in others it is associated with bravery and strength. In addition to the Big Dipper, Ursa Major is home to several other bright stars, including Alioth, Dubhe, and Merak. These stars form the distinctive shape of the Great Bear, with Alioth marking the bear''s tail, Dubhe marking the bear''s back, and Merak marking the bear''s front paw. Overall, Ursa Major is a prominent and interesting constellation that has played a significant role in human history and culture for thousands of years. It is a great subject to observe and learn about, whether you are an experienced stargazer or just starting out.', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/86/UrsaMajorCC.jpg'),
('Cassiopeia', 'Cassiopeia is a constellation located in the northern sky. It is named after a queen in Greek mythology and is easily recognizable due to its distinctive "W" shape, which is formed by a group of bright stars. Cassiopeia is located near the North Pole and is visible throughout the year in the northern hemisphere. Cassiopeia is home to several bright stars, including Schedar, Caph, and Ruchbah. These stars form the distinctive "W" shape of the constellation, with Schedar marking the center of the "W" and Caph and Ruchbah marking the two ends. In addition to its bright stars, Cassiopeia also contains several interesting celestial objects. The constellation is home to several star clusters and nebulae, including the Heart and Soul Nebulae and the Cassiopeia Cluster. It is also home to several binary star systems, making it a rich area for astronomical study. Overall, Cassiopeia is a fascinating constellation to observe and learn about. Its distinctive shape and rich history make it a popular subject for stargazers and astronomers alike.', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c1/CassiopeiaCC.jpg'),
('Scorpius', 'Scorpius is a constellation located in the southern sky. It is named after a scorpion in Greek mythology and is easily recognizable due to the presence of several bright stars. Scorpius is located near the center of the Milky Way galaxy and is visible from much of the world, although it is best seen from the southern hemisphere. Scorpius is home to several bright stars, including Antares, Shaula, and Lesath. Antares is one of the brightest stars in the night sky and marks the heart of the scorpion in the constellation. Shaula and Lesath mark the stinger of the scorpion. In addition to its bright stars, Scorpius also contains several interesting celestial objects. The constellation is home to several star clusters and nebulae, including the Cat''s Paw Nebula and the Rho Ophiuchi Cloud Complex. It is also home to several binary star systems, making it a rich area for astronomical study. Overall, Scorpius is a prominent and interesting constellation to observe and learn about. Its distinctive shape and rich history make it a popular subject for stargazers and astronomers alike.', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4e/ScorpiusCC.jpg')